<script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Can a US or German consumer electronics brand sell wholesale into Ukrainian retail without setting up a Ukrainian legal entity?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Cross-border B2B model through our Ukrainian operational partner under agency agreement. Your brand remains a US LLC / UK Ltd / German GmbH / French SAS / Italian SpA. We sell on your behalf to Ukrainian retail chains (Allo, Foxtrot, Comfy, Epicentre, Rozetka). All Ukrainian roles (legal entity for chain contracts, VAT registration, qualified electronic signature for EDI, Ukrainian Radio Frequency Center (УДЦР) IMEI registration as importer-of-record, alcohol/pharma licenses where applicable) are on our side. You receive monthly settlement in USD or EUR to your home-country bank account. Currency risk of Ukrainian hryvnia is on us — Ukrainian retail pays us in UAH, we convert at NBU daily rate and remit to you."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How does Ukrainian electronics 3PL cost compare to US and EU 3PL?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Pallet storage with ESD zone: $10/mo Ukraine vs $35-50/mo US (Texas/Pennsylvania) vs $40-65/mo EU (Poland/Germany). Pick & pack with IMEI scan: $0.41/order Ukraine vs $1.20-1.80/order US (ShipBob/ShipMonk wholesale) vs $1.80-2.50/order EU (FIEGE, Rhenus). Annual cost for 50 pallets + 200 B2B orders/month: $6,000-7,000 Ukraine vs $24,000-30,000 US vs $30,000-40,000 EU. 3-5x cost arbitrage driven by Ukrainian labor cost ($600-800/mo warehouse worker vs $3,000-4,500 US, $2,200-2,800 EU) and warehouse real estate cost ($35-50/sqm/year vs $120-180 US, $100-150 EU). Quality (99.98% pick accuracy, IMEI rack-level tracking, ANSI/ESD S20.20) is comparable to US/EU specialized electronics 3PL because we run the same WMS technology stack."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is rack-level IMEI/serial number tracking actually possible in a Ukrainian 3PL?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, and this is our key differentiator. Most Ukrainian 3PLs (Unipost, Nova Poshta Fulfillment, Meest, Rozetka FBR) handle electronics as generic SKU — one SKU = one quantity counter without serial number attribution. We track every IMEI/SN at 4 stages: (1) receiving — IMEI bound to import declaration (ВМД) + HS code 8517/8471/8518; (2) rack slotting — IMEI mapped to specific shelf location (e.g., slot A12-B3) in WMS; (3) pick — barcode scan verification of IMEI at pick station with ESD wrist strap; (4) shipping — IMEI populates invoice, packing list, and Nova Poshta Cargo waybill via EDI. Log retained 7 years for warranty trace, customs audit, and anti-grey-market disputes. This is the same model ShipMonk runs in US for electronics clients — but at Ukrainian cost structure."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What ESD compliance standards does MTP follow?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Our ESD-protected zone meets ANSI/ESD S20.20:2021 (US standard) + ДСТУ IEC 61340-5-1 (Ukrainian standard, equivalent to IEC 61340-5-1:2016 international). Specifications: antistatic floor coating (resistance 10^6-10^9 ohms), grounded shelving with continuous ESD ground, ESD wrist straps for all handlers, humidity controlled 40-60% RH (prevents both static buildup and capacitor degradation), antistatic packaging materials (Static Shielding Bags, ESD foam, conductive bubble wrap), regular ESD testing of zone with calibrated meter. Critical for: motherboards, GPUs, network cards, premium audio components (audiophile DACs), Apple original accessories where reputation impact of static damage exceeds packaging cost. We also follow IPC-A-610 Class 2 acceptance criteria for electronics handling — same standard used by enterprise IT distributors globally."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do you handle Li-ion battery storage and shipping compliance?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Li-ion batteries are IATA Class 9 dangerous goods (UN 3480 for batteries shipped alone, UN 3481 for batteries packed with or contained in equipment). Our compliance: dedicated Li-ion storage zone with temperature control +10°C to +25°C, isolated electrical wiring (separate breaker), gas-based fire suppression system (water-based suppression damages electronics), minimum 3m separation from other goods, ventilation. For devices with batteries <100 Wh — standard rack storage. For >100 Wh (power stations, large powerbanks, e-bike batteries, laptop main batteries) — restricted to 2 levels per rack maximum, mandatory UN 3480/3481 marking on outer cartons, transport only by IATA Class 9 licensed carriers. Documentation: Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) for each battery SKU on file, transport via Nova Poshta Cargo Class 9 or specialized carriers (DHL, FedEx, Schenker for international segments)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What does cross-border transportation cost from US, UK, Germany, China, UAE to Ukraine?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"US→Ukraine: $2,500-4,000 per 40ft container by sea (30-45 days via Odesa port) or $8-12/kg by air freight (15-21 days to Boryspil). UK→Ukraine: $1,800-2,800 per 40ft container road+sea (10-15 days) or $5-8/kg air (3-5 days). Germany/Poland/Netherlands→Ukraine: $1,200-2,000 per 40ft truck (5-10 days). China→Ukraine: $2,000-3,500 per 40ft container sea (35-50 days via Black Sea/Odesa) or $6-10/kg air (8-15 days). UAE→Ukraine: $1,500-2,800 for 40ft air freight (7-10 days). Turkey→Ukraine: $1,000-1,800 per 40ft truck (5-8 days via Bulgaria) or sea (12-20 days). This is one-time cost per inventory replenishment, not per order. Averages out to $30-80 per pallet for transportation amortized across order volume. UK and EU brands benefit from UK-Ukraine FTA and EU-Ukraine DCFTA — zero or reduced import duties for most HS 85 (electronics) categories. US brands pay standard MFN tariffs typically 0-5% for consumer electronics."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the onboarding timeline for an international electronics brand?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"21-30 business days from contract signing to first shipment to Ukrainian retail chain. Cycle: days 1-3 contract with our Ukrainian operational partner (agency agreement); days 3-7 documentation prep from your side (corporate registration, banking info, commercial invoice, certificate of origin EUR.1 for EU / UK-Ukraine FTA / US-Ukraine MFN, HS code classification 8517/8471/8518/8528, FCC/CE/UKCA certificates for radio devices); days 7-14 international transportation; days 14-16 inbound at our facility (photo-documented receiving, pallet integrity check, IMEI scan at receive station, УДЦР registration of IMEI batch via our partner — 24 hours after physical arrival); days 16-21 supplier registration with target retail chain through our operator; days 21-25 EDI protocol setup (Vchasno for Allo/general, Comarch for АТБ if applicable, SAP Ariba for Metro); days 25-30 first test shipment with full IMEI trace verification. For brands with complex SKU catalogues (1,000+ items) or pharma/audio-with-mic certifications — up to 45 days."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How does УДЦР (Ukrainian Radio Frequency Center) IMEI registration work for international brands?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Since 2009, mandatory IMEI registration in УДЦР is required for all imported smartphones (and Bluetooth/WiFi devices) before legal sale in Ukraine. Without УДЦР status, retailers like Allo/Foxtrot/Comfy will not accept the device — it's classified as grey market. For international brands, the challenge: УДЦР registration requires Ukrainian importer-of-record. Through our agency model, our Ukrainian operator is the importer-of-record for your inventory. After physical receiving at our warehouse, IMEI batch (or full SN range) is registered with УДЦР via our partner-provider within 24 hours. Status visible to retailers in УДЦР database. This is non-trivial — most international brands attempting Ukraine market entry independently hit this barrier and require local distributor setup. We solve it through agency structure."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What's the war risk for our electronics inventory in Ukraine?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Real consideration. Our Kyiv-region facilities are 35-45 km from city center (Shchaslyve 2,700 sqm primary B2B site, Bilohorodka 1,000 sqm secondary) — outside primary missile impact zones, but Kyiv region experiences air raid alerts and occasional strikes. Mitigation layers: (1) Inventory war-risk insurance via Ukrainian insurers covering warehoused goods, $0.30-0.80 per $100 of inventory value monthly — electronics typically falls in higher-tier due to high unit value, budget $0.60-0.80 per $100. (2) Standard practice of keeping ~30 days of inventory in Ukraine, not 90+ days — fast replenishment cycle reduces static exposure. (3) Distributed retail delivery means inventory moves out within 3-7 days of pick request. (4) Physical hardening: generator backup (Diesel + LPG), blast-protective measures on critical doors, fire suppression. (5) Zero days of operational downtime since February 2022 across our customer base. (6) Government compensation scheme for war-damaged commercial property available. Most international clients include war-risk insurance as standard line item ($1,200-3,000/mo for typical inventory $300K-500K) and operate normally."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How is your service different from Ukrainian generalist 3PLs (Nova Poshta Fulfillment, Unipost, Meest)?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"None of the Ukrainian generalist 3PLs has a dedicated electronics fulfillment page or declares rack-level IMEI tracking — verify on their websites directly. They handle electronics as generic SKU: one SKU = one stock counter without serial number attribution. This means: (a) you cannot prove which specific IMEI shipped to which retailer during warranty disputes; (b) no UDCR registration workflow — you'd need to set this up independently; (c) no ESD-compliant zone — risk of static damage to motherboards, GPUs, premium audio components; (d) no Li-ion segregation — fire risk and potential carrier rejection. MTP built this infrastructure specifically because we have critical mass of electronics distributors. Our model is closer to ShipMonk's electronics specialization (US) or Fulfyld (US) — but at Ukrainian labor and real estate cost structure. The 3-5x cost arbitrage versus US/EU is real because the same WMS technology stack runs on cheaper Ukrainian operational layer."}}]}</script>
